BMC Software, Cabot Oil & Gas, Clearwire: U.S. Equity Movers

-- B y   I n y o u n g   H w a n g
-- 
2011-07-28T20:23:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-27/akamai-bmc-software-citrix-royal-caribbean-visa-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses. Prices are as of 4 p.m. in  New York .  Akamai Technologies Inc. (AKAM)   dropped 19 percent, the
most in the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index, to $23.84. The operator
of a server network that lets businesses deliver data quickly
forecast third-quarter revenue of no more than $283 million,
less than the average analyst estimate of $288.7 million.  BMC Software Inc. (BMC)   erased 8.8 percent, the most
since October 2008, to $44.61. The business-software maker
reported first-quarter sales of $502.4 million, missing the
average analyst estimate of $508.3 million.  Boston Scientific Corp. (BSX)   climbed 8.5 percent, the
most since March 2009, to $7.28. The second-biggest maker of
heart devices boosted its full-year profit forecast, saying it
may earn as much as 70 cents a share.  Cabot Oil & Gas Corp. (COG)   rallied 6.9 percent to
$75.83, the highest price since 1990. The Houston-based natural
gas producer reported second-quarter earnings of 41 cents a
share, topping the average analyst estimate of 27 cents.  Cameron International Corp. (CAM)   rose 9.2 percent, the
most since March 2009, to $55.23, the most intraday since June
2009. The maker of oilfield equipment increased its full-year
profit forecast to as much as $2.65 a share. Analysts, on
average, estimated $2.60, according to a Bloomberg survey.  Cisco Systems Inc. (CSCO)   gained 2 percent to $16.01 for
the biggest increase in the  Dow Jones Industrial Average . The
largest maker of networking gear was raised to “buy” from
“neutral” at Goldman Sachs Group Inc., which cited the outlook
for higher earnings estimates.  Exxon Mobil Corp. (XOM)   fell 2.2 percent to $81.46 for
the second-biggest retreat in the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
The largest U.S. oil company reported second-quarter earnings of
2.18 a share, missing the average analyst estimate by 6.8
percent, Bloomberg data show.  Green Mountain Coffee Roasters Inc. (GMCR)   jumped the
most in the Russell 1000 Index, rallying 16 percent to $102.57.
The Waterbury, Vermont-based company said 2012 profit excluding
some items may be as much as $2.65 a share, more than the
average analyst estimate of $2.19 a share.  Hill-Rom Holdings Inc. (HRC)   tumbled 17 percent, the
most since August 1999, to $36.25. The maker of hospital beds
and stretchers reduced the high end of its full-year earnings
forecast to $2.30 a share, missing the average analyst estimate
of $2.33 in a Bloomberg survey.  Interpublic Group of Cos. (IPG US) slipped 16 percent, the
most since November 2008, to $10.13. The New York-based
advertising company reported second-quarter revenue of $1.74
billion, trailing the average analyst estimate of $1.75 billion
in a Bloomberg survey.  Logitech International SA (LOGI)   slumped 6.8 percent to
$9.61, the lowest price since March 2009. The world’s biggest
maker of computer mice posted a first-quarter loss that was
wider than analysts’ estimates after sales in the  Europe ,  Middle
East  and Africa region declined. Gerald Quindlen stepped down as
president and chief executive officer, the company said, with
Chairman Guerrino De Luca taking on the additional role of
acting president and CEO.  LSI Corp. (LSI)   rose the most in the  S&P 500 , rallying
14 percent to $7.35. The maker of chips used in computer disk
drives forecast third-quarter sales from continuing operations
of $535 million to $565 million. Analysts had predicted $510.7
million on average.  Oshkosh Corp. (OSK)   slumped 13 percent, the most since
April 2009, to $24.96. The U.S. military’s biggest supplier of
armored trucks said fiscal third-quarter earnings fell 68
percent, reflecting decreased sales of military, fire and
emergency trucks.  Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd. (RCL)   fell 13 percent, the
most since July 2009, to $31.26. The world’s second-largest
cruise operator said its 2011 earnings would be $2.95 a share at
most, less than the average analyst estimate of $3.17 a share.  Skechers U.S.A. Inc. (SKX)   soared 19 percent, the most
since April 2009, to $16.95. The maker of Shape-ups toning shoes
was raised to “buy” from “hold” at BB&T Capital Markets,
which cited the odds of “greater earnings power” from a
recovery in gross margin and reduced operating expenses.  Sprint Nextel Corp. (S)   declined 16 percent, the most
since December 2008, to $4.34. The third-biggest U.S. mobile-
phone carrier reported a loss for the 15th consecutive quarter
as more customers dropped their contracts.  Rival  Clearwire Corp. (CLWR)   dropped 22 percent to
$2.15, the biggest drop in the Russell 1000 Index.  Strayer Education Inc. (STRA)   sank 15 percent, the most
since Jan. 10, to $122.25. The holding company of Strayer
University forecast third-quarter earnings of $1.06 a share at
most. On average, the analysts surveyed by Bloomberg estimated
earnings of $1.37 a share.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Inyoung Hwang in New York at 
 ihwang7@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net . 